

               TPUTUNER - A Turbo Pascal Code Optimizer
          ==================================================


What the heck...?
------------------

  TPUTUNER optimizes a Turbo Pascal unit (.tpu) to achieve better
  performance, and smaller code size. Therefore, the unit is
  disassembled, optimized and assembled again.

  TPUTUNER supports Turbo Pascal 6.0 (resp. TPW 1.5), and Borland
  Pascal 7.0; the format is selected at compile time.

  [[ This is a translation of the original German readme file. The
  source code remains commented mostly in German. ]]


Invocation
-----------

  tputuner unit.tpu [target.tpu] [options]

  The target file can be different from the unit file, to keep the
  original. The following options are allowed:

  -a, --data-flow-analysis
  -j, --reduce-jump-chains
  -p, --peephole-optimizations
  -u, --remove-unused-code
  -e, --early-jump
  -l, --late-jump
  -r, --reg-alloc
  -m, --sort-moves
  -c, --combine-strings
  -g, --cse
       Choose the optimisations to perform. By default, all but -r, -c
       and -g are on. To disable one option, use capital letters
       (`-A') or add a "--no" to the long option (`--no-early-jump').
       See below for option descriptions.

  -d, --debug-dump
       Enables generation of debug dumps, see below.

  -n, --names
       When enabled (default), TPUTUNER reads symbol tables and shows
       names of the processed functions in its status messages. If
       this is problematic or annoying, disable with `-N' / `--no-names'.

  -s, --size
       Optimize for size, not speed. May generate instructions that
       are slower (more memory accesses) but need less code.

  -3, --386
       Enables use of 386 instructions. By default, TPUTUNER reads and
       writes 286 code.


Status Messages
----------------

  During run, TPUTUNER displays messages of the following format:

  - code block #248... 1! 2 3 r1  --> 47 bytes saved (new size = 1247)
                 \      \      \       \__ code size reduction this block
                  \      \      \__ Reassembler passes
                   \      \__ Optimizer passes
                    \__ Code block number

  + Code block numbers: the first procedure has number 0, the next is
    8, then 10, 18, etc (hex), no matter in what order they're declared.

  + Optimizer passes: `!' marks passes that yielded improvements.
    After two passes with identical results, tputuner stops.

  + Reassembler passes: usually only one; there can be more when
    reassembly causes some addresses to change because jumps can be
    coded shorter.


Error messages
---------------

  These messages cause TPUTUNER to ignore the respective block. This
  recognizes code which TPUTUNER would damage (I/O, interrupt calls,
  data in code segment, etc.)

  `Unrecognized opcode xx'
  `Direct interrupt access'
  `FPU is not supported' und ähnliche
    TPUTUNER can't disassemble all instructions. It does not recognize
    386+ insns, `test', most flag and string insns, and port I/O.

  `Warning: code block contains bad relocation entries'
    You were taking the absolute address of a label somehow (can only
    be done in inline assembly). TPUTUNER can't handle that.

  `Unrecognized relocation item at...'
    A relocation entry was encountered where TPUTUNER didn't expect
    it. Basically, this means an address literal in code, as per
    `asm @foo: dw offset @foo; end'.


Inline Assembler
-----------------

  ... will be happily processed by TPUTUNER. This is a feature:
  TPUTUNER has no chance of separating Pascal and Assembler code,
  anyway. This allows jump reduction (`jmp finish'...`finish: Exit;')
  and elimination of memory transfers (`a := Random(10); asm mov ax,a
  ...'). Critical assembly code hopefully gets rejected because it
  contains unsupported insns.

  Inline functions are also optimized. Say,
    function successor(i:integer):integer; inline($58/$40);
    ...
    j:=successor(3);
  is compiled to
     push 3
     pop  ax     ; $58
     inc  ax     ; $40
     mov  [j],ax
  TPUTUNER turns the push/pop combo into
     mov  ax,3

  .obj files are generally not optimized, because Turbo assigns them a
  single code block with multiple entries. TPUTUNER can't handle that.


Optimisations
--------------

  Most optimisations are about removing code. This doubtlessly makes
  programs smaller: just count bytes. It generally also makes them
  faster, but that property can't be measured as objectively (counting
  cycles from spec books? not on a Pentium!) But when theres less to
  do for your CPU, and when more of your program fits in the cache, it
  ought to be faster :-)


* Data flow analysis (--data-flow-analysis)

  Eliminates superfluous instructions, when the results they produce
  are already available. These include mostly only load instructions,
  and some logic insns. Probably the correct name for this one would
  be  `reload optimisation', but `data flow analysis' sounds much
  cooler ;-)

  + Example:
        p^.a := 1;
        p^.b := 2;
    compiled to
        les(2)    di, [ss:bp+6]
        mov(2)    [es:di+0], 1
        les(2)    di, [ss:bp+6]
        mov(2)    [es:di+2], 2
    TPUTUNER removes the second LES.

  + Counterexample: aliasing
        p := @a;
        a := b + 1;
        inc(p^);
        b := a + 1;
    compiled to:
        lea(2)    ax, [ss:bp+8]            ; p := @a
        mov(2)    dx, ss
        mov(2)    [ss:bp+fffffffc], ax
        mov(2)    [ss:bp+fffffffe], dx
        mov(2)    ax, [ss:bp+6]            ; a := b + 1
        inc(2)    ax
        mov(2)    [ss:bp+8], ax
        les(2)    di, [ss:bp+fffffffc]     ; inc(p^)
        inc(2)    [es:di+0]
        mov(2)    ax, [ss:bp+8]        **  ; b := a + 1
        inc(2)    ax
        mov(2)    [ss:bp+6], ax

    The original code increments b thrice, the optimized code only
    twice. The line marked ** is removed as being superfluous, "because
    AX already contains [ss:bp+8]". I have not seen such a thing in
    real code, though.

  + Counterexample: register parameters
                mov     si,offset foo
                mov     di,si
                call    bar  { Source in SI, Target in DI }
    optimized to
                mov     di, offset foo
                call    bar
    TPUTUNER assumes that SI only serves for initialisation of DI.


* Jump chain removal (--reduce-jump-chains)

  When a jump jumps to another jump, TPUTUNER jumps to the target
  directly. This happens in constructs like
         IF foo THEN BEGIN
           IF bar THEN qux ELSE frob
         END ELSE fred;


* `Peephole' optimisations (--peephole-optimizations)

  Replace complex insns by simpler ones. Sort of `search & replace',
  and should be safe with TP code. Code is only looked at through a
  peephole of usually 2 or 3 instructions:
                cmp(2)  ax, 0
  is turned into
                or(2)   ax, ax
  in any context.

  In addition, this optimisation replaces some unit SYSTEM calls by
  inline assembly instructions (see tpufmt.h), and simplifies the FOR
  initialisation part.


* Unused code removal (--remove-unused-code)

  Removes unreferenced code, which results from jump chain removal,
  for example. Usually safe, except when one puts data in code...


* Jump earlier (--early-jump)

  Jumps earlier when at the jump target the same instructions would be
  performed as before the jump. This happens quite often, especially
  when longints or strings are in play. TPUTUNER also recognizes some
  blocks as being the same when they slightly differ. This
  optimisation requires the unused code removal be enabled (`-u').

  + Example:
                cmp     [xxx], 1        IF xxx=1 THEN
                jne     skip
                push    10                func(10)
                call    func
                jmp     done            ELSE
        skip:   push    9                 func(9);
                call    func
        done:
    can be reduced to
                cmp     [xxx], 1
                jne     skip
                push    10
                jmp     done
        skip:   push    9
        done:   call    func


* Jump later (--late-jump)

  Similar to `--early-jump', but this one delays jumps. This may not
  save space, but the resulting code may be better parallelizable
  (because there are some insns between the jump's test and the jump).

  + Example:
                cmp     [xxx],1         IF xxx=1 THEN
                jne     skip
                push    10                Fred(10)
                call    Fred
                jmp     done            ELSE
        skip:   push    10                Barney(10);
                call    Barney
        done:
    shortened to
                cmp     [xxx],1
                push    10
                je      skip
                call    Fred
                jmp     done
        skip:   call    Barney
        done:


* Size reduction (--size)

  Most optimisations both improve speed and program size. Some code
  reductions, however, hurt performance. TPUTUNER will only do these
  when you request optimisation for size. Example:
                mov     [foo], ss
                mov     es, [foo]
  is not modified without this option. --size turns it into
                mov     [foo], ss
                push    ss
                pop     es
  which is slower (more memory accesses), but 2 bytes shorter.
  TPUTUNER can not remove the first mov, because the value in [foo]
  may be needed again later.

  Actually, code can also get slower without `-s', in obscure cases
  with `--reg-alloc'.


* Register allocation (--reg-alloc)

  This optimisation makes TPUTUNER put frequently used values and
  addresses into registers. These can be constants, local variables,
  and addresses. In small procedures without subroutine calls, local
  variables cna be held in registers completely.

  This optimisation is off by default, because it is rather time
  consuming. Because it sometimes undoes the DFA's effects (but always
  yield better results), it can only be used when DFA does no longer
  find anything to improve.

  + Example:
                var1 := 7;
                var2 := 7;
                var3 := 7;
    compiled to
                mov     [var1],7
                mov     [var2],7
                mov     [var3],7
    optimized to
                mov     cx,7
                mov     [var1],cx
                mov     [var2],cx
                mov     [var3],cx

    The latter is shorter and usually faster (fewer memory accesses,
    faster instructions, better parallelizable).


* Sort move instructions (--sort-moves)

  Sorts `mov' insns. Peephole optimisations can then combine them to
  store 16 or 32 bit at once. However, this makes lock variables useless:
        lock := TRUE;
        critical1 := 1;
        critical2 := 42;
        lock := FALSE;
  Depending on addresses, both `lock' assignments will be sorted at
  the beginning or end.

  This optimisation is part of peephole optimisation, hence the latter 
  must be enabled when you use --sort-moves.


* Common Subexpression Elimination (--cse)

  Approximately what CSE does in "real" compilers: remove repeating
  code snippets. TPUTUNER looks for code sequences of the form
        <codeA>
        <codeB>
        <codeA>
  where <codeB> does not destroy <codeA>'s result. Here, the second
  <codeA> can be deleted. For example, `p^.q^.x := p^.q^.y;' is
  compiled to
        les     di, [p]             \  codeA
        les     di, [es:di+10]      /
        mov     ax, [es:di]         >  codeB
        les     di, [p]             \
        les     di, [es:di+10]      /  codeA
        mov     [es:di+2], ax
  The second address computation can be omitted.

  This optimisation is off by default, because
  + it is slow. The common code search routine is O(n^2) at least.
  + pointer aliasing problems are especially hard here. TPUTUNER has a 
    simple aliasing recognition for this part (but NO aliasing checks
    for the rest!). It remains to check how hard it is to bypass it,
    when both <codeA> and <codeB> write to [es:di+10], aliasing is
    assumed. Because Pascal has no pointer arithmetic, problems should 
    be rare...


* String combination (--combine-strings)

  (not yet done) Turbo Pascal only combines common string constants
  within a function. This optimisation does the same, for a whole
  unit. It must be quite conservative, though, to not destroy other
  constants (floats, for example).

  NOTE 10/Oct/2000: I'll probably not finish this one. It's quite ugly 
  to write, and doesn't give much.


* Using 386 insns (--386)

  Generates 386 instructions:
  + jcc j16
  + setcc r/m8
  + push i32, push m32
  + mov r/m32, i32

  The 32-bit insns do not appear in debug listings; they are listed as 
  two 16-bit insns at the same address:
        98:  push(2)   [es:di+ffffffea]
        98:  push(2)   [es:di+ffffffe8]
  This is what would be a `push(4) [es:di+ffffffe8]'.

  TPUTUNER can not read back in such units.


* TPUTUNER does not...

  + precompute constants: the compiler should have done this by the
    extent possible.

  + Loop Unrolling.

  + Function Inlining.

  + optimize EXE files. TPUs still have a notice which value is an
    address and which not, EXEs do not have that.

  + Aliasing recognition: TPUTUNER assumes no value is accessible over 
    two access paths, e.g. both via a pointer and a fixed address.
    Basically, we assume all pointers were declared with the C
    `restrict' modifier and no variable is `volatile'. Turbo Pascal
    assumes just the opposite.


Results
--------

  TPUTUNER can shorten most units by 2..10%. I think that's quite a
  usable result.

  Examples:

  + PCC (approx. version 0.99.5):
    - approx. 40 KLOC + 5 KLOC library code (not optimized)
    - normal Turbo Pascal code:
       cc.exe  112144
       cc.ovr  352649
             = 464793
    - optimized with `tputuner -3sE', version approx. 11/1998:
       cc.exe  110256
       cc.ovr  341475
             = 451731 (13062 = 2.8% saved)

  + PCC (v1.0.6.3-debug):
    - about. 70 KLOC
    - normal Turbo Pascal code:
       cc.exe  244544
       cc.ovr  642800
             = 887344
    - optimized with `tputuner -3rg', version 10/2000:
       cc.exe  230672
       cc.ovr  583492
             = 814164 (73180 = 8.2% saved)

  (such huge interactive programs should probably be only optimized
  for size -- response times never have been problematic)

  The most important optimisations are data flow analysis (`-a'),
  early jump (`-e') and CSE (`-g'). The others only yield marginal
  improvements.


Supporting the Optimizer
-------------------------

  When every byte/cycle counts...

  + Simple statments / WITH: TPUTUNER generally only manages one level 
    of indirection. CSE can do more, but doesn't catch everything.
  + Assignment chains / using values directly after computing thems.
    This can re-use register values.
  + Group variables: variables which are often used together should be 
    declared next to each other. So they can be initialized en bloc.
  + Declare small, frequently-used variables first (-> 8 bit displacements).
  + Declare variables that are often passed by-value in pairs next
    each other, so they can be passed to callees an bloc: static 
    variables/record elements as `VAR y, x:INTEGER', locals as
    `VAR x, y:INTEGER' (-> `foo(x,y)'.


Debug Listings
---------------

  Debug listings (--debug-dump) have names `blockX.passY' (`blockX.pY'
  in DOS) where X is the block number in hex, and y is the decimal
  pass number. Only optimizer passes are logged.

  The format is about this:

  1a:  mov(2)    cx, 3
            \__ operand size
  1f:  callf     <un=13,rt=30,rb=30,ro=0>
          \                  \___ Relocation entry
           \___ `call far', as opposed to `call near'
  24:  mov(2)    [ss:bp+6], ax
  2e:  jcc`c'    <label:38>
         \            \_ target is a Label (which currently is at 38hex)
          \_ Conditional jump with Condition Code (jcc`c' == jl, opcode 7Ch),
             similar for setcc (setcc`c' == setl, opcode 0Fh 9Ch).
  38:  label`1'  <38>
   \          \_ Reference count for labels (hex) = how many jumps
    \            refer here
     \_ Address (Hex)

  Sometimes, instructions get an additional operand by TPUTUNER
  (e.g. `xor(2)  ax, ax, 0').

  TPUTUNER also generates 386 insns when 386 code is not enabled. The
  assembler will then split them again.

  TPUTUNER does not analyze relocation entries, except for knowing
  some SYSTEM calls, and that `ro=' can be used to compute the
  distance between two otherwise identical entries. The SYSTEM calls
  we know are long_mul, long_sqr, long_shl, long_shr, and sload;
  see tpufmt.h.


Compiling TPUTUNER
-------------------

  I generally compiler TPUTUNER under Linux with gcc-2.8.1 or later,
  or under DOS with DJGPP 2.02, using the enclosed makefile and GNU
  make.

  TPUTUNER isn't actually what I would call "nice". It started as one
  of my first C++ programs. Probably it has memory leaks like hell. In
  addition, most comments are in German. Good luck.


